Report

Objective: Make a prediction model to classify the arrival delay status of a flight

Analysis

Data Prep

Data is first cleaned by removing columns that are not useful and/or have many missing values. Especially for target variable, arr_delay, the whole row of data has to be removed as the target variable should not be manipulated. The two datasets are merged through time columns which have the same values. After which, columns with few missing values are imputed with median or mode values (which is selected after looking at the distribution of the variable and choosing a good majority value), to complete all entries in dataset.

Feature Engineering
New columns are created to have features to aid the subsequent modelling ability.

head(joined)
##   month day hour           time_hour dep_time sched_dep_time dep_delay
## 1     1   1   10 2013-01-01 10:00:00     1010           1015        -5
## 2     1   1   13 2013-01-01 13:00:00     1314           1315        -1
## 3     1   1   15 2013-01-01 15:00:00     1513           1505         8
## 4     1   1   15 2013-01-01 15:00:00     1457           1500        -3
## 5     1   1   17 2013-01-01 17:00:00     1725           1730        -5
## 6     1   1   18 2013-01-01 18:00:00     1825           1829        -4
##   sched_arr_time arr_delay carrier tailnum  temp  dewp humid wind_dir
## 1           1210 Not Delay      US  N162UW 41.00 28.04 59.65      260
## 2           1505 Not Delay      US  N177US 39.20 28.40 69.67      330
## 3           1703     Delay      EV  N13914 37.94 24.08 57.04      290
## 4           1656 Not Delay      US  N539UW 37.94 24.08 57.04      290
## 5           1926 Not Delay      US  N680AW 35.96 19.04 49.83      330
## 6           2032     Delay      US  N460UW 33.98 15.08 45.43      310
##   wind_speed precip visib
## 1   13.80936      0    10
## 2   16.11092      0    10
## 3    9.20624      0    10
## 4    9.20624      0    10
## 5   11.50780      0    10
## 6   12.65858      0    10
#convert time_hour from factor to time-based
joined$time_hour <- ymd_hms(joined$time_hour)

#convert tailnum to character
joined$tailnum <- as.character(joined$tailnum)

#create dep_period, hours split into 3 time periods: Morning, Afternoon, Evening
joined <- joined %>% 
  mutate(dep_period = case_when(hour <=10 ~ "Morning",
                                hour >10 & hour <=16 ~ "Afternoon",
                                hour >16 ~ "Evening"))
joined$dep_period <- as.factor(joined$dep_period)

#convert month and hour from integer to factor
joined$hour <- as.factor(joined$hour)
joined$month <- as.factor(joined$month)

#create days of week column
joined$weekdays <- as.factor(weekdays(joined$time_hour))

#create dep_delay_class column (dep_delay<=15 is 0(short), >15 is 1(long))
joined <- joined %>%
  mutate(dep_delay_class = case_when(dep_delay <= 15 ~ 1,
                                     dep_delay >  15 ~ 2))

Exploratory Data Analysis

Data is explored based on time, elapsed air time and weather variables to see if there are more useful information which can be used to classify the flight delays further.

library(ggplot2)
#by month, day, hour
joined %>% 
  group_by(month) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=month, fill=arr_delay))+
  geom_bar()+
  labs(title="Flights by Month", fill="Arrival Delays")

joined$weekdays <- factor(joined$weekdays, levels = c("Monday", "Tuesday", "Wednesday", "Thursday", "Friday", "Saturday", "Sunday"))
ggplot(joined)+
  geom_bar(aes(x=weekdays, fill=arr_delay))+
  facet_wrap(~carrier)+

More feature engineering after exploring data.

#create is_weekend column
joined <- joined %>% 
  mutate(is_weekend = ifelse(weekdays == "Saturday" | weekdays == "Sunday",
                             "Weekend", "Not Weekend"))
joined$is_weekend <- as.factor(joined$is_weekend)

#create bad_weather column using precip and visib
joined <- joined %>% 
  mutate(bad_weather = ifelse(precip >= 0.025 | visib <= 2.5, 2, 1))

#create air_time column (time from departure to scheduled arrival)
joined <- joined %>% 
  mutate(air_time = sched_arr_time - dep_time) %>% 
  mutate(air_time_class = ifelse(air_time < mean(air_time), 2, 1))

#remove not useful columns

Model Fitting

3 Machine Learning algorithms are used to build models, namely K-nearest neighours, random forest and logistic regression. Data is processed according the requirements of each algorithm. The model is cross-validated by splitting the data into train and test sets to carry out evaluation via confusion matrix metrics.

library(class)

As the initial logistic regression model seemed to perform better than the other 2 models, further tuning of the model was carried out. Stepwise method was used to quickly sieve out variables which are good at predicting the delays. However, to avoid overfitting on the training data, some feature engineered variables were swapped with the original variables. This generated a more generalised model which performed equally as good as the stepwise model. In fact, the fit_log2 model used 9 variables whereas the stepwise model gave an optimum model of 10 variables.

Comparing models

Models are compared using the metrics of confusion matrix (Accuracy, Sensitivity, Specificity and Precision). The final model chosen is the logistic regression model as it has the best overall values of all 3 models. The Precision score is slightly low, which means less correctly predicted delays. However, we have managed to have relatively high Accuracy, Sensitivity and Specificity scores, which means less actual delays which are incorrectly predicted and more non delays which are correctly predicted.

#create feature engineered columns
submission <- submission %>% 
  mutate(sched_arr_time = ifelse(sched_arr_minute <10,

submission$sched_dep_time <- as.numeric(submission$sched_dep_time)

submission <- submission %>% 
  mutate(dep_time = sched_dep_time + dep_delay)

submission2 <- submission %>% 
  mutate(is_weekend = ifelse(day == "Saturday" | day == "Sunday", "Weekend", "Not Weekend")) %>% 
  mutate(dep_delay_class = case_when(dep_delay <= 15 ~ 1,
                                     dep_delay >  15 ~ 2)) %>% 
  mutate(bad_weather = ifelse(precip >= 0.025 | visib <= 2.5, 2, 1))
submission2$is_weekend <- as.factor(submission2$is_weekend)
library(tidyr)
sep_dep_time <- submission2 %>% 
  separate(dep_time, into=c("hour", "minute"), sep = -2, convert = TRUE)

submission2$hour <- sep_dep_time$hour

submission2 <- submission2 %>% 
  mutate(dep_period = case_when(hour <=10 ~ "Morning",
                                hour >10 & hour <=16 ~ "Afternoon",
                                hour >16 ~ "Evening")) %>% 
  mutate(air_time = sched_arr_time - dep_time) %>% 
  mutate(air_time_class = ifelse(air_time < mean(air_time), 2, 1))
submission2$dep_period <-  as.factor(submission2$dep_period)
submission2$hour <- as.factor(submission2$hour)

Capstone Task

As a final step in machine learning course, every student should complete ONLY ONE case as their machine learning capstone project.

The dataset and rubrics are attached, separated by Case. Please note that Case 3: Your own data set still comes with a set of rubrics. Ensure that your data set is sufficiently difficult to be able to meet the rubrics before embarking.

Case 1: Food and Beverage The Food and Beverage dataset is provided by Dattabot, which contains detailed transactions of multiple food and beverage outlets. You will be challenged to do some forecasting and time series analysis to help the outlets owner make better business decisions.

Case 2: Airline13: The Late List Flight delays and travel interruptions can put a real strain on travelers wallet, plans and sanity. Major airline companies have begun to develop an early notification system about delays. Using Airline13 dataset, make a prediction model to classify the arrival status (Delay vs Not Delay) of a flight that would be evaluated on December 2013.

Case 3: Your own data set You are free to use your own data set to do machine learning predictions. To ensure that there is sufficient difficulty in the data-set, please discuss with your trainer before embarking on the project. Note that if the data is too clean, it will not make a good project! Be sure to check with your trainers beforehand.
